Prediction of the antenna of good pass through the space.¶

ASAD ASHRAF KAREL

RADAR stands for Radio Detection and Ranging System. It is basically an electromagnetic system used to detect the location and distance of an object from the point where the RADAR is placed. It works by radiating energy into space and monitoring the echo or reflected signal from the objects.¶

About the data:¶

This radar data was collected by a system in Goose Bay, Labrador. This system consists of a phased array of 16 high-frequency antennas with a total transmitted power on the order of 6.4 kilowatts. See the paper for more details. The targets were free electrons in the ionosphere. "good" radar returns are those showing evidence of some type of structure in the ionosphere. "bad" returns are those that do not; their signals pass through the ionosphere.

Received signals were processed using an autocorrelation function whose arguments are the time of a pulse and the pulse number. There were 17 pulse numbers for the Goose Bay system. Instances in this databse are described by 2 attributes per pulse number, corresponding to the complex values returned by the function resulting from the complex electromagnetic signal. See cited below for more details.

Usage¶

data(Ionosphere)

Format¶

A data frame with 351 observations on 35 independent variables, some numerical and 2 nominal, and one last defining the class.

Source¶

Source: Space Physics Group; Applied Physics Laboratory; Johns Hopkins University; Johns Hopkins Road; Laurel; MD 20723 Donor: Vince Sigillito (vgs@aplcen.apl.jhu.edu)

Attribute information¶

Received signals were processed using an autocorrelation function whose arguments are the time of a pulse and the pulse number. There were 17 pulse numbers for the Goose Bay system. Instances in this database are described by 2 attributes per pulse number, corresponding to the complex values returned by the function resulting from the complex electromagnetic signal.

The targets were free electrons in the ionosphere. "Good" (g) radar returns are those showing evidence of some type of structure in the ionosphere. "Bad" (b) returns are those that do not; their signals pass through the ionosphere.

Relevant papers¶

Sigillito, V. G., Wing, S. P., Hutton, L. V., & Baker, K. B. (1989). Classification of radar returns from the ionosphere using neural networks. Johns Hopkins APL Technical Digest, 10, 262-266.

1) Logistic Regression:¶

In [27]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
In [28]:
LR = LogisticRegression(solver = 'saga', max_iter = 200)

LR.fit(Xtrain, ytrain)

print('Accuracy for the train dataset:',LR.score(Xtrain, ytrain))
print('Accuracy for the test dataset:',LR.score(Xtest, ytest).round(3))

Accuracy for the train dataset: 0.9428571428571428
Accuracy for the test dataset: 0.851

Insight:¶

We get 90% accuracy for the train and test data both. Hence our Logistic Algorithm is avoiding overfitting and underfitting in the process. Regression gives a good response. Still we feel 90 should increase to 96-97%.

We saw a basic thing among probabilistic models and deterministic model and technique. We conclude the Logistic Regression showed the awesome output. But still we were facing 10% of error.

If such case comes up a Data Scientist finally approaches to Ensemble Techniques which are extremely awesome and good in working.

Let's see the Ensemble models.¶

Ensemble Techniques¶

We have 3 members in the family of Ensemble Techniques. We eventually mix multple models or single model multiple times the algorithms. This is nothing but Ensemble Technique.

1) Stacking¶

In [81]:
from sklearn.ensemble import VotingClassifier

Prediction:¶

In [117]:
L = ionosphere.drop('class', axis=1)

Grid_etc = ExtraTreesClassifier(bootstrap=True, n_estimators = 20, criterion = 'entropy', max_depth = 7)
Prediction_etc = Grid_etc.fit(Xtrain, ytrain).predict(L)

Etc_Data = pd.DataFrame((np.array(ionosphere['class'].values)), Prediction_etc).reset_index()
Etc_Data = Etc_Data.rename({'index':'Real', 0 : 'Predicted'}, axis = 1)
Etc_Accuracy = (Etc_Data[Etc_Data.Real == Etc_Data.Predicted]).shape[0]/Etc_Data.shape[0]

print('The accuracy on the complete data with Stack Ensemble model is:', round(Etc_Accuracy*100,3),'%')

The accuracy on the complete data with Stack Ensemble model is: 94.017 %

Reason, why Stack-Voting and Extra Tree Classifier is better for data?

  • The first thing is we got 95% accuracy compared to the entire data. Since we observed it was a little imbalanced, even in that cercumstance we got a good accuracy.
  • Even Logistic Regression gave a good accuracy, but the it wasn't on the complete data.

  • And we see, even we had a good accuracy in Logistic Regression, but that was not as good as Stack-Ensemble model.
  • Finally we can say, that Stack-Voting works on each member of the Ensemble family, and we adjusted all the algorithms with their best respeetive parameters. Hence It is preferrable to go with this technique.
  • The same answer is for Extra-Tree-Classifier. Both the algorithms are doing so well. Hence we extracted the data form both the models. Which can be used in further experiments.
